data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely in .NET Core+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no abort mechanism exists
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never thrown** — dead code path

### Migrated Code (using `Task` + `CancellationToken`)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did
            task.Wait(token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // task.Wait() unwraps as AggregateException — preserve original behavior
        return task.Result;
    }

    // Async-native overload (preferred in new code)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        try
        {
            return await work(token).WaitAsync(token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cooperative cancellation** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative* — `work` must check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or pass `token` to I/O APIs. A CPU-bound loop that ignores the token **will not stop**. |
| **No guaranteed termination** | The old code forcibly killed the thread. There is no .NET 8 equivalent. If you truly need forced termination, isolate work in a **separate process**. |
| **`Task.Result` wraps in `AggregateException`** | This matches your original behavior, but callers using `await` will get the inner exception unwrapped instead. |
| **Thread vs ThreadPool** | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool. If `work` is long-blocking, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`. |

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowComputation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After (.NET 8) — pass the token through
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowComputation(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

Inside the work method, honor the token:

```csharp
int SlowComputation(CancellationToken ct)
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // check periodically
        Process(item);
    }
    return total;
}
```

**Bottom line:** The old pattern relied on forcible thread termination — a dangerous operation even in Framework (could corrupt shared state, skip `finally` blocks). The cooperative cancellation model is safer and the only supported path in .NET 8.
